%I A363064 #32 Jul 08 2026 10:46:51
%S A363064 1,1,2,5,12,37,94,280,912,3164,8424,35883,91918
%N A363064 Number of connected Laplacian integral graphs on n vertices.
%C A363064 A (simple, undirected) graph is called Laplacian integral if all eigenvalues of its Laplacian matrix are integers. The corresponding sequence that uses the adjacency matrix instead of the Laplacian matrix is A064731.
%C A363064 Since every cograph is Laplacian integral, a(n) >= A000669(n).
%C A363064 If n is prime, then any Laplacian integral graph on n vertices is the complement of a disjoint union of smaller Laplacian integral graphs. (This fact was used to compute a(13) from a(1)-a(12).) - _Luis M. B. Varona_, Jul 08 2026
%H A363064 R. Grone and R. Merris, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.laa.2007.09.025">Indecomposable Laplacian integral graphs</a>, Linear Algebra and its Applications, 428 (2008), 1565-1570.
%H A363064 N. Johnston, S. Plosker, and L. M. B. Varona, <a href="https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2607.06336">Enumeration of Laplacian integral and {-1,0,1}-diagonalizable graphs</a>, arXiv.2607.06336 [math.CO], 2026.
%H A363064 L. M. B. Varona, <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.21114288">Small {-1,0,1}-Diagonalizable Graphs: A Computational Survey</a>, Zenodo, 2026.
%e A363064 For n <= 3, all connected graphs are Laplacian integral, so a(n) = A001349(n) when n <= 3.
%e A363064 There is exactly one connected graph on 4 vertices that is not Laplacian integral: the path P_4, which has Laplacian matrix
%e A363064    1 -1  0  0
%e A363064   -1  2 -1  0
%e A363064    0 -1  2 -1
%e A363064    0  0 -1  1
%e A363064 which has eigenvalues 0, 2, 2-sqrt(2), and 2+sqrt(2), which are not all integers.
%Y A363064 Cf. A000669, A001349, A064731, A363065 (include disconnected graphs).
%K A363064 nonn,hard,more,changed
%O A363064 1,3
%A A363064 _Nathaniel Johnston_, May 16 2023
%E A363064 a(10) from _M. A. Achterberg_, May 26 2023
